# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: digital-to-analog-conversion
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] In electronics, a **digital-to-analog converter** (**DAC**, **D/A**, **D2A**, or **D-to-A**) is a system that converts a digital signal into an analog signal.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] An analog-to-digital converter (ADC) performs the reverse function.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] DACs are commonly used in music players to convert digital data streams into analog audio signals.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] They are also used in televisions and mobile phones to convert digital video data into analog video signals.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] These two applications use DACs at opposite ends of the frequency/resolution trade-off.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] The audio DAC is a low-frequency, high-resolution type, while the video DAC is a high-frequency low- to medium-resolution type.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] There are several DAC architectures; the suitability of a DAC for a particular application is determined by figures of merit, including: resolution, maximum sampling frequency and others.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] Digital-to-analog conversion can degrade a signal, so a DAC should be specified that has insignificant errors in terms of the application.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] Due to the complexity and the need for precisely matched components, all but the most specialized DACs are implemented as integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] These typically take the form of metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) mixed-signal integrated circuit chips that integrate both analog and digital circuits.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] Discrete DACs (circuits constructed from multiple discrete electronic components instead of a packaged IC) would typically be extremely high-speed, low-resolution, power-hungry types, as used in military radar systems.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] Very high-speed test equipment, especially sampling oscilloscopes, may also use discrete DACs.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] A DAC converts an abstract finite-precision number (usually a fixed-point binary number) into a physical quantity (e.g., a voltage or a pressure).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] In particular, DACs are often used to convert finite-precision time series data to a continually varying physical signal.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] Provided that a signal's bandwidth meets the requirements of the Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem (i.e., a baseband signal with bandwidth less than the Nyquist frequency) and was sampled with infinite resolution, the original signal can theoretically be reconstructed from the sampled data.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] However, an ADC's filtering can't *entirely* eliminate all frequencies above the Nyquist frequency, which will alias into the baseband frequency range.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] And the ADC's digital sampling process introduces some quantization error (rounding error), which manifests as low-level noise.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] These errors can be kept within the requirements of the targeted application (e.g. under the limited dynamic range of human hearing for audio applications).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] In a typical telephone call, a microphone converts speech into an analog electrical signal, which is digitized by an ADC.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] The resulting digital data can be multiplexed with other digital information for transmission over a shared communication system.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] At the receiving end, a DAC converts the digital signal back into analog form so it can be amplified and reproduced as sound.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] Early CD players used oversampling ahead of the D/A converter so that the analog reconstruction filter could be of low order and have a well-controlled phase response.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] In 1982, Philips described such a system in detail.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] A 16-bit, 44.1 kHz input is first applied to a digital interpolation filter and oversampled by a factor of four to 176.4 kHz.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] The interpolation filter is a 96-tap finite impulse response network.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] Its passband extends over the audio range, while the stopband attenuates the image components that would otherwise appear between 22 kHz and 88 kHz after zero-order hold conversion.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] The higher sampling rate shifts these images away from the audio band and reduces the requirements on the analog filter.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] The filtered sequence is then represented with 14-bit precision and applied to the Philips TDA1540.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] This converter employs segmented current sources.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] The larger current elements are subdivided and switched in a manner that averages element errors over time, an early form of dynamic element matching.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] The result is improved linearity compared with a straightforward binary-weighted current source.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] At the output of the converter, the waveform consists of a staircase approximation to the desired signal, together with residual high-frequency components from the sampling process.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] A third-order analog low-pass filter follows the converter.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] This filter removes the remaining out-of-band energy and provides the final smoothing of the waveform.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] A later device, the Philips TDA1541, provides full 16-bit resolution and removes the need for the intermediate word-length reduction step.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] In this and later designs, the same general arrangement was retained.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] This arrangement, digital interpolation followed by conversion and a relatively simple analog filter, became standard practice in CD playback and appears in later DACs such as the Crystal CS4397.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] Most modern audio signals are stored in digital form (for example, MP3s and CDs), and in order to be heard through speakers, they must be converted into an analog signal.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] DACs are therefore found in CD players, digital music players, and PC sound cards.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] Specialist standalone DACs can also be found in high-end hi-fi systems.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] These normally take the digital output of a compatible CD player or dedicated transport (which is basically a CD player with no internal DAC) and convert the signal into an analog line-level output that can then be fed into an amplifier to drive speakers.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] Similar digital-to-analog converters can be found in digital speakers, such as USB speakers and in sound cards.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] In voice over IP applications, the source must first be digitized for transmission, so it undergoes conversion via an ADC and is then reconstructed into analog using a DAC on the receiving party's end.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] Video signals from a digital source, such as a computer, must be converted to analog form if they are to be displayed on an analog monitor.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] As of 2007, analog inputs were more commonly used than digital, but this changed as flat-panel displays with DVI and/or HDMI connections became more widespread.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] A video DAC is, however, incorporated in any digital video player with analog outputs.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] The DAC is usually integrated with some memory (RAM), which contains conversion tables for gamma correction, contrast and brightness, to make a device called a RAMDAC.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] A device that is distantly related to the DAC is the digitally controlled potentiometer, used to control an analog signal digitally.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] A one-bit mechanical actuator assumes two positions: one when on, another when off.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] The motion of several one-bit actuators can be combined and weighted with a whiffletree mechanism to produce finer steps.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] The IBM Selectric typewriter uses such a system.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] DACs are widely used in modern communication systems, enabling the generation of digitally defined transmission signals.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] High-speed DACs are used for mobile communications and ultra-high-speed DACs are employed in optical communications systems.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] The number of possible output levels the DAC is designed to reproduce.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] , which is a measurement of the actual resolution attained by the DAC.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] The maximum speed at which the DACs circuitry can operate and still produce correct output.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] A measurement of the distortion and noise introduced to the signal by the DAC.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] and noise that accompanies the desired signal.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] Other measurements, such as phase distortion and jitter, can also be very important for some applications, some of which (e.g., wireless data transmission, composite video) may even *rely* on accurate production of phase-adjusted signals.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] Non-linear PCM encodings (A-law / μ-law, ADPCM, NICAM) attempt to improve their effective dynamic ranges by using logarithmic step sizes between the output signal strengths represented by each data bit.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/digital-to-analog-converter] This trades greater quantization distortion of loud signals for better performance of quiet signals.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] PWM is useful for controlling the average power or amplitude delivered by an electrical signal.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The average value of voltage (and current) fed to the load is controlled by switching the supply between 0 and 100% at a rate faster than it takes the load to change significantly.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The longer the switch is on, the higher the total power supplied to the load.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Along with maximum power point tracking (MPPT), it is one of the primary methods of controlling the output of solar panels to that which can be utilized by a battery.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] PWM is particularly suited for running inertial loads such as motors, which are not as easily affected by this discrete switching.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The goal of PWM is to control a load; however, the PWM switching frequency must be selected carefully in order to smoothly do so.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The PWM switching frequency can vary greatly depending on load and application.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Choosing a switching frequency that is too high for the application may cause premature failure of mechanical control components, despite getting smooth control of the load.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Selecting a switching frequency that is too low for the application causes oscillations in the load.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The main advantage of PWM is that power loss in the switching devices is very low.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] When a switch is off, there is practically no current, and when it is on and power is being transferred to the load, there is almost no voltage drop across the switch.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Power loss, being the product of voltage and current, is thus in both cases close to zero.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] PWM also works well with digital controls, which, because of their on/off nature, can easily set the needed duty cycle.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] PWM has also been used in certain communication systems where its duty cycle has been used to convey information over a communications channel.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The term *duty cycle* describes the proportion of 'on' time to the regular interval or 'period' of time; a low duty cycle corresponds to low power, because the power is off for most of the time.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Duty cycle is expressed in percent, 100% being fully on.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] When a digital signal is on half of the time and off the other half of the time, the digital signal has a duty cycle of 50% and resembles a "square" wave.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] When a digital signal spends more time in the on state than the off state, it has a duty cycle of >50%.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] When a digital signal spends more time in the off state than the on state, it has a duty cycle of <50%.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The Corliss steam engine was patented in 1849.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] It used pulse-width modulation to control the intake valve of a steam engine cylinder.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] A centrifugal governor was used to provide automatic feedback.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Some machines (such as a sewing machine motor) require partial or variable power.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] In the past, control (such as in a sewing machine's foot pedal) was implemented by use of a rheostat connected in series with the motor to adjust the amount of current flowing through the motor.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] It was an inefficient scheme, as this also wasted power as heat in the resistor element of the rheostat, but tolerable because the total power was low.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] While the rheostat was one of several methods of controlling power (see autotransformers and Variac for more info), a low-cost and efficient power switching and adjustment method was yet to be found.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] This mechanism also needed to be able to drive motors for fans, pumps and robotic servomechanisms, and needed to be compact enough to interface with lamp dimmers.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] PWM emerged as a solution for this complex problem.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] PWM telecommunications systems were invented just prior to the start of World War II, but at that time time-division multiplexing was already in use and there were only experimental PWM systems.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] This changed with the introduction of the cavity magnetron in 1940, which could produce pulses of microwave frequency energy but could not vary its frequency or precisely control its amplitude.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] A PWM encoder was used to trigger a magnetron in the British Army's Wireless Set Number 10, which provided long-distance telephone relay, up to 80 kilometres (50 mi).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] V. company had designed an optical scanning system for variable area film soundtrack which used PWM while it was scanning the optical audio track transversely with a thin light beam.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The electronics then evaluated the threshold between exposed (non-translucent) and unexposed (translucent) parts of the audio track.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The proposed system was to reduce noise when playing a film soundtrack.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] One early application of PWM was in the Sinclair X10, a 10 W audio amplifier available in kit form in the 1960s.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] At around the same time, PWM started to be used in AC motor control.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] In the mid-1970s, early automotive applications of pulse-width modulation (PWM) were developed in the UK by Associated Engineering Developments Ltd (AED).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Engineers Norman Hunt and John Noddings designed systems that used pulse-width modulated electrical signals to control high-speed solenoid valves.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] By altering the signal's duty cycle, the system could vary hydraulic and pneumatic pressure instead of just turning a solenoid valve fully open or fully closed.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] This technology was commercialised through AED's subsidiary company, Econocruise Ltd, based in Rugby, Warwickshire.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The company used these modulated solenoid valves in pneumatic assemblies to control throttle actuators, supplying cruise control systems for luxury passenger cars and PWM speed limiters for heavy commercial trucks and buses.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] This latter expression can be fairly simplified in many cases where $y_{\text{min}}=0$ as ${\bar {y}}=D\cdot y_{\text{max}}$ .
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] From this, the average value of the signal ( ${\bar {y}}$ ) is directly dependent on the duty cycle D.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] However, by varying (i.e. modulating) the duty cycle (and possibly also the period), the following more advanced pulse-width modulated waves allow variation of the average value of the waveform.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The intersective method is a simple way to generate a PWM output signal (magenta in above figure) with fixed period and varying duty cycle is by using a comparator to switch the PWM output state when the input waveform (red) intersects with a sawtooth or a triangle waveform (blue).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Many digital circuits can generate PWM signals (e.g., many microcontrollers have PWM outputs).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] They normally use a counter that increments periodically (it is connected directly or indirectly to the clock of the circuit) and is reset at the end of every period of the PWM.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] When the counter value is more than the reference value, the PWM output changes state from high to low (or low to high).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] This technique is referred to as **time proportioning,** particularly as **time-proportioning control** – which *proportion* of a fixed cycle time is spent in the high state.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The incremented and periodically reset counter is the discrete version of the intersecting method's sawtooth.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The analog comparator of the intersecting method becomes a simple integer comparison between the current counter value and the digital (possibly digitized) reference value.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The duty cycle can only be varied in discrete steps, as a function of the counter resolution.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] However, a high-resolution counter can provide quite satisfactory performance.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The resulting spectra (of the three alignments) are similar.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Each contains a DC component, a base sideband containing the modulating signal, and phase modulated carriers at each harmonic of the frequency of the pulse.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The amplitudes of the harmonic groups are restricted by a $\sin x/x$ envelope (sinc function) and extend to infinity.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The infinite bandwidth is caused by the nonlinear operation of the pulse-width modulator.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] In consequence, a digital PWM suffers from aliasing distortion that significantly reduce its applicability for modern communication systems.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] By limiting the bandwidth of the PWM kernel, aliasing effects can be avoided.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] On the contrary, delta modulation and delta-sigma modulation are random processes that produces a continuous spectrum without distinct harmonics.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] While intersective PWM uses a fixed period but a varying duty cycle, the period of delta and delta-sigma modulated PWMs varies in addition to their duty cycle.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Delta modulation produces a PWM signal (magenta in the above figure) which changes state whenever its integral (blue) hits the limits (green) surrounding the input (red).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Asynchronous (i.e., unclocked) delta-sigma modulation produces a PWM output (blue in bottom plot) which is subtracted from the input signal (green in top plot) to form an error signal (blue in top plot).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] This error is integrated (magenta in the middle plot).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] When the integral of the error exceeds the limits (the upper and lower grey lines in the middle plot), the PWM output changes state.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] By integrating the difference of the error with the input signal, delta-sigma modulation shapes noise of the resulting spectrum is more concentrated in higher frequencies above the input signal's band.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Direct torque control is a method used to control AC motors.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] It is closely related to the delta modulation (see above).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Motor torque and magnetic flux are estimated and these are controlled to stay within their hysteresis bands by turning on a new combination of the device's semiconductor switches each time either signal tries to deviate out of its band.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The process of PWM conversion is non-linear, and it is generally supposed that low-pass filter signal recovery is imperfect for PWM.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] In electronics, many modern microcontrollers (MCUs) integrate **PWM controllers** exposed to external pins as peripheral devices under firmware control.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] These are commonly used for direct current (DC) motor control in robotics, switched-mode power supply regulation, and other applications.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The type of PWM controller found in MCUs is based on a digital counter.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] In the basic output mode, the counter is compared against a threshold level to determine whether a signal should be output.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] As a result, the threshold level determines the duty cycle.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] (This is a digital version of the intersective method from above.) Some PWMs include a way to control the period/frequency, either a configurable clock divider or a "prescaling" counter.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Many PWM controllers are also input devices: they can measure the characteristics (frequency, duty cycle) of an input PWM signal using their inbuilt counters and triggers that fire at the falling or rising edge of the input signal.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Using two edges of the same type produces the frequency/period; using two edge measurements of different types produces the "on" or "off"-duration, which when divided by period produces the duty cycle.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] PWM is used to control servomechanisms; see servo control.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The PWM output of a microcontroller is almost never used to directly drive a motor.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Instead, this signal is interpreted by a motor controller, which converts it into a more accurate PWM signal for the motor.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] This kind of "PWM controller" used in robotics is derived from PWM controllers used in hobby radio control vehicles.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] In telecommunications, PWM is a form of signal modulation where the widths of the pulses correspond to specific data values encoded at one end and decoded at the other.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Pulses of various lengths (the information itself) will be sent at regular intervals (the carrier frequency of the modulation).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The inclusion of a clock signal is not necessary, as the leading edge of the data signal can be used as the clock if a small offset is added to each data value to avoid a data value with a zero length pulse.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] PWM can be used to control the amount of power delivered to a load without incurring the losses that would result from linear power delivery by resistive means.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Drawbacks to this technique are that the power drawn by the load is not constant but rather discontinuous (see Buck converter), and energy delivered to the load is not continuous either.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] However, the load may be inductive, and with a sufficiently high frequency and when necessary using additional passive electronic filters, the pulse train can be smoothed and an average analog waveform recovered.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Power flow into the load can be continuous.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Power flow from the supply is not constant and will require energy storage on the supply side in most cases.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] High frequency PWM power control systems are easily realisable with semiconductor switches.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] As explained above, almost no power is dissipated by the switch in either on or off state.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] However, during the transitions between on and off states, both voltage and current are nonzero and thus power is dissipated in the switches.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] By quickly changing the state between fully on and fully off (typically less than 100 nanoseconds), the power dissipation in the switches can be quite low compared to the power being delivered to the load.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Modern semiconductor switches such as MOSFETs or insulated-gate bipolar transistors (IGBTs) are well-suited components for high-efficiency controllers.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Frequency converters used to control AC motors may have efficiencies exceeding 98%.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Switching power supplies have lower efficiency due to low output voltage levels (often even less than 2 V for microprocessors are needed), but still more than 70–80% efficiency can be achieved.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Variable-speed computer fan controllers usually use PWM, as it is far more efficient when compared to a potentiometer or rheostat.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Light dimmers for home use employ a specific type of PWM control.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Home-use light dimmers typically include electronic circuitry that suppresses current flow during defined portions of each cycle of the AC line voltage.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Adjusting the brightness of light emitted by a light source is then merely a matter of setting at what voltage (or phase) in the AC half-cycle the dimmer begins to provide electric current to the light source (e.g. by using an electronic switch such as a triac).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] In this case the PWM duty cycle is the ratio of the conduction time to the duration of the half AC cycle defined by the frequency of the AC line voltage (50 or 60 Hz, depending on the country).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Some other types of light sources, such as light-emitting diodes (LEDs), however, turn on and off extremely rapidly and would perceivably flicker if supplied with low-frequency drive voltages.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Perceivable flicker effects from such rapid-response light sources can be reduced by increasing the PWM frequency.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] If the light fluctuations are sufficiently rapid (faster than the flicker fusion threshold), the human visual system can no longer resolve them, and the eye perceives the time average intensity without flicker.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] In electric cookers, continuously variable power is applied to the heating elements, such as the hob or the grill, using a device known as a simmerstat.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] This consists of a thermal oscillator running at approximately two cycles per minute, and the mechanism varies the duty cycle according to the knob setting.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The thermal time constant of the heating elements is several minutes, so that the temperature fluctuations are too small to matter in practice.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] PWM is also used in efficient voltage regulators.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] By switching the voltage to the load with the appropriate duty cycle, the output will approximate a voltage at the desired level.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The switching noise is usually filtered with an inductor and a capacitor.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] When it is lower than the desired voltage, it turns on the switch.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] When the output voltage is above the desired voltage, it turns off the switch.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] PWM techniques would typically be used to make some indicator (like an LED) *soft blink*.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The light will slowly go from dark to full intensity, and then slowly dim to dark again.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The period would be several soft blinks per second, up to several seconds for one blink.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] An indicator of this type would not disturb as much as a *hard-blinking* on/off indicator.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The indicator lamp on the Apple iBook G4, PowerBook 6,7 (2005) was of this type.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] This kind of indicator is also called *pulsing glow*, as opposed to calling it *flashing*.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Varying the duty cycle of a pulse waveform in a synthesis instrument creates useful timbral variations.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Some synthesizers have a duty-cycle trimmer for their square-wave outputs, and that trimmer can be set by ear; the 50% point (true square wave) is distinctive because even-numbered harmonics essentially disappear at 50%.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Pulse waves, usually 50%, 25%, and 12.5%, make up the soundtracks of classic video games.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The term PWM as used in sound (music) synthesis, refers to the ratio between the high and low levels being secondarily modulated with a low-frequency oscillator.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] This gives a sound effect similar to chorus or slightly detuned oscillators played together.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Class-D amplifiers produce a PWM equivalent of a lower frequency input signal that can be sent to a loudspeaker via a suitable filter network to block the carrier and recover the original lower frequency signal.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Since they switch power directly from the high supply rail and low supply rail, these amplifiers have efficiency above 90% and can be relatively compact and light, even for large power outputs.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] For a few decades, industrial and military PWM amplifiers have been in common use, often for driving servomotors.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Field-gradient coils in MRI machines are driven by relatively high-power PWM amplifiers.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Historically, a crude form of PWM has been used to play back PCM digital sound on the PC speaker, which is driven by only two voltage levels, typically 0 and 5 V.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The Sega 32X uses PWM to play sample-based sound in its games.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] This method is used in the SACD format, and reproduction of the encoded audio signal is essentially similar to the method used in class-D amplifiers.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] SPWM (sine–triangle pulse-width modulation) signals are used in solar inverter design.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] These switching signals are fed to the FETs that are used in the device.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] The device's efficiency depends on the harmonic content of the PWM signal.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] There is much research on eliminating unwanted harmonics and improving the fundamental strength, some of which involves using a modified carrier signal instead of a classic sawtooth signal in order to decrease power losses and improve efficiency.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/pulse-width-modulation] Another common application is in robotics where PWM signals are used to control the speed of the robot by controlling the motors.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] A **resistor ladder** is an electrical circuit made from repeating units of resistors, in specific configurations.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] An R–2R ladder configuration is a simple and inexpensive way to perform digital-to-analog conversion (DAC), using repetitive arrangements of precise resistor networks in a ladder-like configuration.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] The paper gives an advantage of R–2R that impedances seen by the sources are more equal.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] Another historic description is in US Patent 3108266, filed in 1955, "Signal Conversion Apparatus".
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] A string of many resistors connected between two reference voltages is called a "resistor string".
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] The resistors act as voltage dividers between the referenced voltages.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] A Kelvin divider or *string DAC* is a string of equal valued resistors.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] Each tap of the string generates a different voltage, which can be compared with another voltage: this is the basic principle of a flash ADC (analog-to-digital converter).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] The main disadvantage is that this architecture requires $2^{n}$ comparators, one for each resistor; and this number cannot be reduced by using an R-2R network because such a network would not have separate outputs for each voltage.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] A resistor string can function as a DAC by having the bits of the binary number control electronic switches connected to each tap.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] The binary weighted configuration uses power of two multiples of a base resistor value.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] However, as the ratios of resistor values increases, the ability to trim the resistors to accurate ratio tolerances becomes diminished.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] More accurate ratios can be obtained by using similar values, as is used in R–2R ladder.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] Hence R–2R provides more accurate digital-to-analog conversion.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] A *voltage mode* R–2R resistor ladder network is shown in Figure 1.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] It produces an analog output voltage $V_{out}$ from a digital integer D composed of n bits: $a_{n-1}$ (most significant bit, MSB) through bit $a_{0}$ (least significant bit, LSB), which are driven from digital logic gates.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] The bit inputs are switched between 0 volts (logic 0) and *V*ref volts (logic 1).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] The R–2R ladder is inexpensive and relatively easy to manufacture, since only two resistor values are required (or even one, if R is made by placing a pair of 2R in parallel, or if 2R is made by placing a pair of R in series).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] It is fast and has fixed output impedance R.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] The R–2R ladder operates as a string of current dividers, whose output accuracy is solely dependent on how well each resistor is matched to the others.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] Small inaccuracies in the MSB resistors can entirely overwhelm the contribution of the LSB resistors.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] This may result in non-monotonic behavior at major crossings, such as from 011112 to 100002.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] Depending on the type of logic gates used and design of the logic circuits, there may be transitional voltage spikes at such major crossings even with perfect resistor values.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] These can be filtered with capacitance at the output node (the consequent reduction in bandwidth may be significant in some applications).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] Finally, the 2R resistance is in series with the digital-output impedance.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] High-output-impedance gates (e.g., LVDS) may be unsuitable in some cases.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] For all of the above reasons (and doubtless others), this type of DAC tends to be restricted to a relatively small number of bits; although integrated circuits may push the number of bits to 14 or even more, 8 bits or fewer is more typical.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] The R–2R DAC described above directly outputs a voltage and so is called *voltage mode* (or sometimes *normal mode*).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] Since the output impedance is independent of digital code, the analog output may equally-well be taken as a current into a virtual ground, a configuration called *current mode* (or sometimes *inverted mode*).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] Using *current mode*, the gain of the DAC may be adjusted with a series resistor at the reference voltage terminal.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] The current for all bits pass through an equivalent resistance of 2R to ground.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] The less significant the bit, the more resistors its signal must pass through.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] At each node each bit's current is divided by two.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] Resistors used with the more significant bits must be proportionally more accurate than those used with the less significant bits; for example, in the R–2R network discussed above, inaccuracies in the bit-4 (MSB) resistors must be insignificant compared to 1⁄32 (~3.1%) of R.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] Further, to avoid problems at the 100002-to-011112 transition, the sum of the inaccuracies in the lower bits must also be significantly less than that.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] The required accuracy doubles with each additional bit: for 8 bits, the accuracy required will be better than 1⁄256 (~0.4%).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] However, variances for resistances when manufactured in a single component tend to be much lower than variances between components or between batches of manufacturing, and hence a resistor network can be purchased as a single component.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] And within integrated circuits, R–2R networks may be printed directly onto a single substrate using thin-film technology for higher accuracy.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] Even so, they must often be laser-trimmed to achieve the required precision.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] Such on-chip resistor ladders for digital-to-analog converters achieving 16-bit accuracy have been demonstrated.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] It is not necessary that each "rung" of the R–2R ladder use the same resistor values.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] It is only necessary that the "2R" value matches the sum of the "R" value plus the Thévenin-equivalent resistance of the lower-significance rungs.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] Figure 2 shows a linear 4-bit DAC with unequal resistors.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] This allows a reasonably accurate DAC to be created from a heterogeneous collection of resistors by forming the DAC one bit at a time.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] At each stage, resistors for the "rung" and "leg" are chosen so that the rung value matches the leg value plus the equivalent resistance of the previous rungs.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/r-2r-ladder] The rung and leg resistors can be formed by pairing other resistors in series or parallel in order to increase the number of available combinations.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/zero-order-hold] The **zero-order hold** (**ZOH**) is a mathematical model of the practical signal reconstruction done by a conventional digital-to-analog converter (DAC).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/zero-order-hold] That is, it describes the effect of converting a discrete-time signal to a continuous-time signal by holding each sample value for one sample interval.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/zero-order-hold] It has several applications in electrical communication.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/zero-order-hold] The function $\mathrm {rect} \left({\frac {t-T/2}{T}}\right)$ is depicted in Figure 1, and $x_{\mathrm {ZOH} }(t)$ is the piecewise-constant signal depicted in Figure 2.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/zero-order-hold] The equation above for the output of the ZOH can also be modeled as the output of a linear time-invariant filter with impulse response equal to a rect function, and with input being a sequence of dirac impulses scaled to the sample values.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/zero-order-hold] The filter can then be analyzed in the frequency domain, for comparison with other reconstruction methods such as the Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula suggested by the Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem, or such as the first-order hold or linear interpolation between sample values.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/zero-order-hold] In this method, a sequence of Dirac impulses, *x*s(*t*), representing the discrete samples, *x*[*n*], is low-pass filtered to recover a continuous-time signal, *x*(*t*).
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/zero-order-hold] The scaling by T , which arises naturally by time-scaling the delta function, has the result that the mean value of *xs*(*t*) is equal to the mean value of the samples, so that the lowpass filter needed will have a DC gain of 1.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/zero-order-hold] Some authors use this scaling, while many others omit the time-scaling and the *T*, resulting in a low-pass filter model with a DC gain of *T*, and hence dependent on the units of measurement of time.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/zero-order-hold] The effective frequency response is the continuous Fourier transform of the impulse response.
[src:digital-to-analog-conversion/zero-order-hold] This drop is a consequence of the *hold* property of a conventional DAC, and is *not* due to the sample and hold that might precede a conventional analog-to-digital converter (ADC).
